# Title of prerequisites popup which describes prerequisites before reading some articles
msgid "Prerequisites"
msgstr ""

msgid "You should read the following articles prior to following this tutorial:"
msgstr ""

msgid "A small slope over the bridge"
msgstr ""

msgid "A banked curve"
msgstr ""

msgid "A long slope"
msgstr ""

msgid "When to measure performance?"
msgstr ""

msgid "There are a few situations that warrant measuring the game’s performance:"
msgstr ""

msgid "Trying to optimize your settings to get the best balance of visual quality and smoothness for your taste."
msgstr ""

msgid "Designing a track and [ensuring performance is good](Making_Tracks:_Optimization). Even if it's acceptable on your machine, think of players that might have weaker hardware."
msgstr ""

msgid "Testing the effect of code changes that are supposed to improve performance or that carry a significant computational load that may degrade performance."
msgstr ""

msgid "Or just [comparing your hardware’s performance with other users](https://forum.supertuxkart.net/thread-43.html)."
msgstr ""

msgid "Using the built-in FPS counter"
msgstr ""

msgid "The built-in FPS counter’s main advantage is how easy it is to activate it : just go in the UI options and toggle the relevant checkbox."
msgstr ""

msgid "A purple bar then shows up at the top of your screen. It contains three FPS values : minimum FPS, current FPS, maximum FPS. It also contains a few other informations relevant for track creator such as the polycount."
msgstr ""

msgid "However, this method suffers from several limitations: it is rater inaccurate, the current FPS value is a poor indicator as its doesn’t capture the effect of short spikes, and the values change between tests as the driving is different each time."
msgstr ""

msgid "This makes it impossible to reliably assess the effect of small performance changes (<15%) or the significance of small stutters, which play a major role in perceived smoothness."
msgstr ""

msgid "Using the built-in benchmark"
msgstr ""

msgid "The built-in performance test available starting with SuperTuxKart 1.5 is a good solution to those issues."
msgstr ""

msgid "**Because it uses a replay, it is highly repeatable and even small differences of a few percent can be identified.** The built-in replay uses the most demanding standard track, making it particularly useful for the optimization of graphics settings and the test of hardware performance."
msgstr ""

msgid "Note that your camera settings can also slightly influence the results as they change how much of the track the game has to render."
msgstr ""

msgid "Furthermore, the metrics displayed at the end of the test give their proper importance to short spikes in frame duration that degrade player experience. This is explained in more detail in [the blog post presenting the benchmark tool](https://blog.supertuxkart.net/2024/07/why-average-fps-and-1-low-fps-are.html)."
msgstr ""

msgid "To use it, simply go to the ‘Graphics’ options menu and click on the ‘Performance test of the current settings’ button."
msgstr ""

msgid "**Online multiplayer is noticeably more CPU-intensive than single player, so if you want to play online, you may want to include some extra margin.**"
msgstr ""

msgid "Adding a custom benchmark"
msgstr ""

msgid "Finally, the last method is to use a custom replay with the built-in performance test tool. This allows to test any track of your choice."
msgstr ""

msgid "This is especially useful for track creators, who obviously need to test their own track and not one already present in the game. **If you follow [the track optimization guide](Making_Tracks:_Optimization), this is a great way to measure the effects of your changes.**"
msgstr ""

msgid "The first step is to record a replay. Select time-trial mode, and after having selected your track simply check the appropriate checkbox to record your race."
msgstr ""

msgid "Depending on what system you are using, replay files can be found in one of the following folders:"
msgstr ""

msgid "On Windows:"
msgstr ""

msgid "On Linux:"
msgstr ""

msgid "On Mac OS X:"
msgstr ""

msgid "Once you have your replay, the next step is to tell the game to use it."
msgstr ""

msgid "With SuperTuxKart 1.5, the only way is to replace the contents of ‘benchmark_black_forest.replay’ located in the game’s ‘data/replay’ folder with the contents of your replay file, preferably after backing up the original file."
msgstr ""

msgid "With the latest development version, and, when they release, with SuperTuxKart 1.5.1 and SuperTuxKart Evolution, the game can detect multiple benchmark files."
msgstr ""

msgid "First add your file to the ‘data/replay’ folder, then open ‘stk_config.xml’ located in the ‘data’ folder and look for ‘benchmark’. Add another ‘file’ entry following the model of the one already present, with the name of your replay."
msgstr ""

msgid "Once this is done, simply start the game and go to the ‘Graphics’ option menu. Below the button to start the test, you will find a new UI element with which you can select which of the available benchmark files you want to use."
msgstr ""

msgid "From this point on, everything is the same as for the standard built-in benchmark."
msgstr ""

msgid "The limitation of this method is that it relies on a replay, so it is currently not possible to test battle arenas and soccer fields without extra tricks."
msgstr ""

# Posters page
msgid "On this page you will find SuperTuxKart's official posters."
msgstr ""

# Posters page
msgid "You can enlarge them by clicking on the picture, and you can download them by clicking the 'Download' button in the caption."
msgstr ""

# Posters page - section title
msgid "Archived posters"
msgstr ""

# Posters page - a credit for one of the posters
msgid "Credit: Mariam Lamrani"
msgstr ""

# Projects page
msgid "Due to the libre and open source nature of SuperTuxKart, the game is used in various research project, studies or simply prototypes made by fans."
msgstr ""

# Projects page
msgid "On this page, you can discover various projects that have been done with our game."
msgstr ""

# Projects page
msgid "If you have a project using SuperTuxKart not listed here, or if you want to use the game in your own project, you can contact us."
msgstr ""

# Projects page - section title
msgid "Driver Development"
msgstr ""

# Projects page - section title
msgid "Tyr"
msgstr ""

# Projects page
msgid "SuperTuxKart was used as a target for the development of Tyr, a driver for the Mali GPUs found in ARM SoCs, porting the C code of Panthor to Rust."
msgstr ""

# Projects page
msgid "In November 2025, Tyr's ability to render SuperTuxKart races at low settings with reasonable performance for the tested SoC was showcased in Collabora's [blog post about Tyr's progress](https://www.collabora.com/news-and-blog/news-and-events/racing-karts-on-a-rust-gpu-kernel-driver.html) as well as through [a video](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=wX9cTGenBDk) showing STK played with the new driver."
msgstr ""

# Projects page - section title
msgid "Technical Demonstrations"
msgstr ""

# Projects page - section title
msgid "A Mercedes as SuperTuxKart Controller"
msgstr ""

# Projects page
msgid "When it comes to driving a car in the real world, the big touchscreens that have become commonplace in modern cars are often distracting. And a real car is a tad expensive to use as a gaming device."
msgstr ""

# Projects page
msgid "Nonetheless, when Mercedes-Benz showcased SuperTuxKart being played with a car's controls at the 2019 Mobile World Congress, [journalists were wowed](https://www.theverge.com/2019/2/27/18243256/mario-kart-mercedes-benz-daimler-driving-game-mwc-2019)."
msgstr ""

# Projects page
msgid "Many outlets referred to 'Mario Kart' in their reporting, probably because any kart game is 'Mario Kart' to some, but it's SuperTuxKart which powered this impressive demo. And perhaps this carelessness in naming could be seen as a testament to SuperTuxKart quality."
msgstr ""

# Projects page
msgid "STK's open nature further allowed Mercedes to synchronize the car's lighting, air conditioning and even seatbelt with in-game events, making the experience exceptional."
msgstr ""

# Projects page - section title
msgid "Cybersecurity Researchers Use a Car to Play at SuperTuxKart"
msgstr ""

# Projects page
msgid "The Controller Area Network (CAN) bus is used by modern cars to pass on data between different parts of the vehicle."
msgstr ""

# Projects page
msgid "Intercepting and injecting messages on the CAN bus can allow hacking a car, for good or bad purposes. SuperTuxKart was used at least twice by cybersecurity researchers to demonstrate the interception of messages on the CAN bus:"
msgstr ""

# Projects page
msgid "In 2024, researchers from Darmstatd University showcased [in a DEFCON presentation](https://media.defcon.org/DEF%20CON%2032/DEF%20CON%2032%20presentations/DEF%20CON%2032%20-%20Timm%20Lauser%20Jannis%20Hamborg%20-%20Redefining%20V2G%20-%20How%20to%20use%20your%20vehicle%20as%20a%20game%20controller.pdf) the use of intercepted CAN data from a Volkswagen ID.3 to play at SuperTuxKart using the car as a controller, using a separate screen placed in front of the car to display the game."
msgstr ""

# Projects page
msgid "In 2025, security researchers from Pen Test Partners [made a similar demo](https://www.pentestpartners.com/security-blog/how-we-turned-a-real-car-into-a-mario-kart-controller-by-intercepting-can-data/) on a 2016 Renault Clio."
msgstr ""

msgid "A Volkswagen ID.3 used as a SuperTuxKart gaming wheel"
msgstr ""

# Projects page - section title
msgid "Microsoft IllumiRoom Demo"
msgstr ""

# Projects page
msgid "[IllumiRoom](https://www.microsoft.com/en-us/research/project/illumiroom-peripheral-projected-illusions-for-interactive-experiences/) was a proof-of-concept system from Microsoft Research."
msgstr ""

# Projects page
msgid "It used projected visualizations around a television screen to enhance the traditional living room entertainment experience."
msgstr ""

# Projects page
msgid "Showcased in 2013, it featured SuperTuxKart 0.8 in [its demo video](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=re1EatGRV0w&t=49s), with white circles projected on the wall representing falling snow."
msgstr ""

msgid "Illumiroom with SuperTuxKart 0.8 on the TV"
msgstr ""

# Projects page - section title
msgid "Virtual Joystick using Kinect"
msgstr ""

# Projects page
msgid "The [Gesture Therapy platform](https://pdfs.semanticscholar.org/b3f1/36317f77d67d269d09c2005254fe52baae49.pdf) is a system for upper limb rehabilitation developed by a Mexican team."
msgstr ""

# Projects page
msgid "In 2013, to showcase the capabilities of the Virtual Joystick system it uses, they released a [demo video](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=8vSfHG7BHUk) showing the acceleration and steering of a kart in SuperTuxKart 0.8 being controlled through the movements of an arm."
msgstr ""

# Projects page - section title
msgid "Academic Research and Teaching"
msgstr ""

# Projects page - section title
msgid "A Reduction of Imitation Learning and Structured Prediction to No-Regret Online Learning"
msgstr ""

# Projects page
msgid "**A landmark paper from 2010 by Stéphane Ross & al introducing the 'DAgger' method for machine learning**, improving the methods of imitation learning. This paper is [still referenced](https://arstechnica.com/ai/2025/07/how-a-big-shift-in-training-llms-led-to-a-capability-explosion/) well over a decade later. **It used SuperTuxKart as a core part of its experiments.**"
msgstr ""

# Projects page
msgid "The [full paper](https://arxiv.org/pdf/1011.0686) is available as well as an [old video](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=V00npNnWzSU) showing the simple machine learning models attempting to drive."
msgstr ""

# Projects page - section title
msgid "Other Machine Learning Projects"
msgstr ""

# Projects page
msgid "SuperTuxKart is used regularly by people learning machine learning at universities. Here are some example of such projects:"
msgstr ""

# Projects page
msgid "A 2022 project combining reinforcement learning with a transformer model to play STK races on Around the Lighthouse ([Github repository](https://github.com/vibalcam/deep-rl-supertux-race) and [full paper](https://github.com/vibalcam/deep-rl-supertux-race/blob/master/deep_rl_supertux_race_report.pdf))"
msgstr ""

# Projects page
msgid "A 2020 project as [part of a course from the University of Texas](https://github.com/jwgrogan/Super-Tux-Kart-AI) using deep learning to play STK's Icy Soccer ([GitHub repository](https://github.com/vibalcam/SuperTuxKart-hockey) and [full paper](https://adivekar.com/files/UTCS-Deep-Learning-Final-Autonomous-agents-for-realtime-multiplayer-ice-hockey.pdf))."
msgstr ""

# Projects page - section title
msgid "Game-Based Rehabilitation for Myoelectric Prosthesis Control"
msgstr ""

# Projects page
msgid "An [Austrian study from 2017](https://games.jmir.org/2017/1/e3/) evaluating the use of video games for the rehabilitation of upper-limb amputees. As, according to the study, many 'prosthesis users abandon their devices due to difficulties in prosthesis control', it explored games as a way to make the training process more enjoyable and efficient."
msgstr ""

# Projects page
msgid "SuperTuxKart is one of the three games that was used as part of the study."
msgstr ""

# Projects page - section title
msgid "Comparing the Effectiveness and Ergonomics of Smartphone-Based Gamepads"
msgstr ""

# Projects page
msgid "A 2024 study from the University of Regensburg setting 24 people to drive in SuperTuxKart, comparing both their objective performance and subjective experience with different smartphone-based gamepads as well as a physical gamepad."
msgstr ""

# Projects page
msgid "The detailed methodology and results highlighted in the [full paper](https://dl.acm.org/doi/fullHtml/10.1145/3670653.3670676) are very interesting."
msgstr ""

# Projects page
msgid "Many participants felt that the absence of shoulder triggers was the biggest limitation of the smartphone-based gamepads (and the STK team agrees)."
msgstr ""

# Projects page
msgid "Smartphones with shoulder triggers are now available on the market. Through this study, SuperTuxKart is playing a small role in making them more common!"
msgstr ""

# Projects page
msgid "The physical gamepad proved noticeably better, despite input latency being equalized between the tested devices."
msgstr ""

# Projects page - section title
msgid "Service-oriented Integration of SuperTuxKart"
msgstr ""

# Projects page
msgid "A [paper from 2022](https://dl.acm.org/doi/abs/10.1007/978-3-031-26507-5_33) proposing the use of a REST API to make it easier for services to interface with the game, and presenting [a possible implementation](https://github.com/rpesl/stk-code)."
msgstr ""

# Projects page - section title
msgid "Concepts for Advanced Integration of SuperTuxKart into Connected Cars"
msgstr ""

# Projects page
msgid "A detailed master's thesis from the University of Stuttgart published in 2021 exploring how a connected car could be used to play games. The [full text is freely available](https://elib.uni-stuttgart.de/bitstream/11682/11901/1/Master%27s%20Thesis.pdf)."
msgstr ""

# Projects page - section title
msgid "A Study on QoE Improvement of Online Games with UDP Multipathization by SDN"
